1 Preface
*********

“Bookmark++” is a fork of Drew Adams' Bookmark+ package, modernized for
GNU Emacs 30 and later.  Bookmark+ supports the entire span of GNU Emacs
from version 20 through 26 — a quarter-century of Emacs history.  To run
on each release the source carried many conditional execution paths,
many fallback implementations of functions that became built-in years
later, runtime probes for keymaps and faces that were not always
present, and duplicated ‘defcustom’ forms with different ‘:type’ widgets
for each Emacs generation.  This fork simplifies it.  It requires GNU
Emacs 30 or later and uses many of the modern built-ins that replaced
coded functionality in Bookmark+.

   Upstream Bookmark+ shipped with two notable third-party integrations
that no longer match how most users work in Emacs 30: a deep tie-in to
Drew Adams' Icicles completion framework, and an active integration with
‘emacs-w3m’ (a popular external web browser in the mid-2000s).  This
fork drops both.  In place of Icicles, Bookmark++ uses plain
‘completing-read’ everywhere and assumes the user brings their own
modern completion stack on top -- ‘vertico’ and ‘consult’ with
‘marginalia’ and ‘orderless’, or ‘helm’, or ‘ivy’, all work without any
package-specific glue (and ‘consult-bookmark’ adds live preview for
free; *note Live Preview::).  In place of ‘emacs-w3m’, Bookmark++ uses
the built-in ‘eww’ browser: legacy W3M bookmarks saved by older sessions
are still recognised by ‘bmkp-w3m-jump’, but their handler routes them
through ‘bmkp-jump-eww’ so they keep working, and no new W3M bookmarks
are created.  This fork also adds an optional Casual Transient menu.
*Note Migration::, for the complete change list.

   The goal of this fork is to retain the original functionality of
Bookmark+.  The only major exception is that it does not replace the
bookmark package by replacing its functionality.  Instead, it provides
functions that are equivalent to it.  For example, ‘bmkp-list’ and
‘bmkp-jump’ instead of redefining ‘bookmark-list’ and ‘bookmark-jump’.
This way, both packages can coexist.  In fact, built-in Bookmark can
read bookmark files created by Bookmark+ and vice-versa.


