2 Introduction
**************

Bookmark+ is a substantial extension of GNU Emacs's built-in
‘bookmark.el’.  It keeps every concept from built-in bookmarks--named,
persistent placeholders into files, buffers, Info nodes, and so on--but
makes bookmarks useful as persistent records, not just saved positions.

   Bookmark+ enlarges built-in bookmarks in three directions:

  1. *Richer bookmarks.*  Bookmarks can carry tags, annotations, region
     information, visit counts, last-access timestamps, and arbitrary
     user data.  They can be highlighted in the buffer they point to,
     and they remember where they were even when the file has been
     edited.

  2. *More kinds of bookmarks.*  In addition to bookmarks that "go" to a
     location, Bookmark+ ships over 70 bookmark types: Dired buffers,
     Info nodes, Gnus articles, EWW pages, ‘man’ pages, image files,
     URLs, desktops, keyboard macros, sets of variables, snippets of
     text, sequences of other bookmarks, whole bookmark files, and more.

  3. *More to do with bookmarks.*  The ‘*Bmkp List*’ buffer is
     significantly enhanced.  You can mark, sort, filter, omit, search,
     query-replace, tag, retag, edit, clone, highlight, describe, and
     copy/move bookmarks across multiple bookmark files.  You can save
     bookmark-list views, define your own jump commands and sort orders,
     and cycle through arbitrary sets of bookmarks ("the navigation
     list").

   *Bookmark+ is an additive sibling of the built-in ‘bookmark.el’.*
Loading this package does _not_ redefine any function from
‘bookmark.el’.  Every command in Bookmark+ lives under the ‘bmkp-’
prefix and is available from its own keymaps (‘C-x x’, ‘C-x j’, ‘C-x 4
j’).  The standard ‘C-x r m’, ‘C-x r b’ and ‘C-x r l’ bindings still
call the built-in.  Both systems read and write the same on-disk
bookmark file format, so you can use either at any time.

   If you would like the standard keys to invoke Bookmark+ instead, see
*note Standard Keys::.


