3 Tutorial
**********

This chapter walks through a typical first session.  Open a few files
you actually use, then follow along.

3.1 Creating Your First Bookmark
================================

Place point somewhere in a file you visit often--say, midway through a
long ‘README’.  Type:

     M-x bmkp-bookmark-set-confirm-overwrite RET

   (The shorter key sequence is ‘C-x x m’.)  Emacs prompts for a
bookmark name; type ‘readme top RET’.  The bookmark is set at point, and
the bookmark file is updated on disk (if ‘bookmark-save-flag’ is ‘t’,
which is the default).

3.2 Opening the Bookmark List
=============================

Type ‘C-x x e’ (or ‘M-x bmkp-list’).  Buffer ‘*Bmkp List*’ appears.  You
see one row per bookmark, in a marked, sortable display.

   Try the basics:

‘n’
     Next line.
‘p’
     Previous line.
‘<RET>’
     Open the bookmark on the current line in the same window.
‘o’
     Open it in another window.
‘<TAB>’
‘C-o’
     _Preview_ it in another window without leaving ‘*Bmkp List*’.
‘q’
     Quit.  The buffer is hidden; your bookmarks stay in memory.

3.3 Adding a Tag
================

In ‘*Bmkp List*’, place point on the bookmark you just created.  Type ‘T
+’ (‘bmkp-add-tags’).  At the ‘Tag(s):’ prompt type ‘doc RET RET’ (the
empty entry ends the list).  A small ‘t’ now appears on that bookmark's
line, indicating it is tagged.

   To list only tagged bookmarks: ‘T S’.  To show all again: ‘.’.

3.4 Jumping
===========

You can jump from anywhere in Emacs:

     C-x j j RET readme top RET

   ‘bmkp-jump’ prompts you with completion; type the bookmark name or
use your usual completion machinery to pick.  If the ‘consult’ package
is loaded, you get live preview as you move through candidates.

   To jump in the other window, use ‘C-x 4 j j’.  To jump only among
bookmarks of a specific type (Dired, Info, EWW, ...), use ‘C-x j :’ and
choose the type.

3.5 Filtering and Sorting
=========================

Open ‘*Bmkp List*’ (‘C-x x e’) and try:

‘s s’
     Cycle through sort orders.  Repeat until something useful.
‘s n’
     Sort by bookmark name.
‘s d’
     Sort by last bookmark access (most recent first).
‘< / >’
     Show only unmarked / marked bookmarks.
‘P B’
     Incremental filter on bookmark name.  Type a regexp; press <RET> to
     commit.
‘.’
     Show all bookmarks again.
‘M-t’
     Toggle the location column (file or buffer name).

3.6 Multiple Bookmarks at Once
==============================

Mark several bookmarks with ‘m’ (or ‘M-m’ to mark all).  Then:

‘T > +’
     Add tags to all marked bookmarks at once.
‘D’
     Delete all marked bookmarks (after confirmation).
‘M-d >’
     Open Dired on every local file among the marked bookmarks.
‘Y > +’
     Copy the marked bookmarks into another bookmark file.

3.7 Live Preview Mode
=====================

Type ‘M-p’ in ‘*Bmkp List*’.  The mode-line lighter changes to ‘ Pv’.
Now moving point onto a row immediately opens that bookmark's
destination in another window--without selecting it.  Press ‘M-p’ again
to turn the mode off; the window configuration is restored to what it
was when you entered the mode.

3.8 Saving and Switching Bookmark Files
=======================================

Your bookmarks live in ‘bookmark-default-file’ (‘~/.emacs.d/bookmarks’
by default), and are saved automatically.  To save explicitly: ‘S’ in
‘*Bmkp List*’.  To switch to a different bookmark file: ‘L’
(‘bmkp-switch-bookmark-file-create’).

   That is the core workflow.  The rest of this manual reads as a
reference: each chapter covers one feature in detail.


