6 Jumping to Bookmarks
**********************

‘bmkp-jump’ (‘C-x j j’) is the generic bookmark jump command; completion
offers every bookmark.  ‘bmkp-jump-other-window’ (‘C-x 4 j j’) is its
other-window twin.  Inside ‘*Bmkp List*’, <RET> or ‘f’ calls
‘bmkp-list-this-window’, and ‘o’ calls ‘bmkp-list-other-window’.

6.1 Type-Specific Jump Commands
===============================

Each bookmark type has its own jump command that offers only bookmarks
of that type as completion candidates.  They live on ‘bmkp-jump-map’
(default ‘C-x j’) and ‘bmkp-jump-other-window-map’ (default ‘C-x 4 j’).
A small sampler:

Type                   Same-window          Other-window
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
File                   ‘C-x j f’            ‘C-x 4 j f’
Local file             ‘C-x j l’            ‘C-x 4 j l’
Remote file            ‘C-x j n’            ‘C-x 4 j n’
Autofile               ‘C-x j a’            ‘C-x 4 j a’
Non-file               ‘C-x j b’            ‘C-x 4 j b’
Dired                  ‘C-x j d’            ‘C-x 4 j d’
Info                   ‘C-x j i’            ‘C-x 4 j i’
‘man’                  ‘C-x j m’            ‘C-x 4 j m’
EWW                    ‘C-x j e’            ‘C-x 4 j e’
Gnus                   ‘C-x j g’            ‘C-x 4 j g’
Image                  ‘C-x j M-i’          ‘C-x 4 j M-i’
Region                 ‘C-x j r’            ‘C-x 4 j r’
URL                    ‘C-x j u’            ‘C-x 4 j u’
Highlighted            ‘C-x j h’            ‘C-x 4 j h’
Snippet                ‘C-x j M-w’          ‘C-x 4 j M-w’

   The generic "any type" command is ‘bmkp-jump-to-type’ (‘C-x j :’).
It first asks for the type, then offers only bookmarks of that type.
Useful when you do not want to remember the type-specific keys.

6.2 ‘find-file’-Style Jumping
=============================

‘bmkp-find-file’ (‘C-x j C-f’) acts like ‘find-file’, but obeys
‘bmkp-default-handlers-for-file-types’--so HTML files open in
‘browse-url’, Word docs in ‘w32-browser’, and so on.  With a prefix
argument it also creates an autofile bookmark for the file.

   There is a family of ‘bmkp-find-file-...-tags’ commands (under ‘C-x j
t C-f ...’) that filter by tags while reading a file name with
‘read-file-name’, so you can browse directories.

6.3 Mode-Specific ‘j’
=====================

Several modes bind ‘j’ to the corresponding type-specific jump:

Mode                      ‘j’ jumps to a...
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
Info                      Info bookmark.
Gnus summary              Gnus bookmark.
‘man’ / ‘woman’           ‘man’-page bookmark.
EWW                       EWW bookmark.
Buffer-menu               Non-file bookmark.
Dired (‘C-j’)             Dired bookmark whose directory is the current
                          one.

6.4 Tag-Based Jumping
=====================

Tag-aware jump commands combine three ideas: which bookmark family
(file, autofile, this-dir-file, find-file), how many tags must match
(all = ‘*’, some = ‘+’), and whether matching is literal or against a
regexp (‘%’).

Command                        Key              Meaning
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
‘bmkp-all-tags-jump’           ‘C-x j t *’      With all given tags.
‘bmkp-some-tags-jump’          ‘C-x j t +’      With at least one tag.
‘bmkp-all-tags-regexp-jump’    ‘C-x j t % *’    Every tag matches a
                                                regexp.
‘bmkp-some-tags-regexp-jump’   ‘C-x j t % +’    Some tag matches a
                                                regexp.
‘bmkp-file-all-tags-jump’      ‘C-x j t f *’    File bookmark with all
                                                tags.
‘bmkp-find-file-all-tags’      ‘C-x j t C-f     ‘read-file-name’
                               *’               version.

   Each command has an ‘-other-window’ twin under ‘C-x 4 j t ...’.


