7 The ‘*Bmkp List*’ Buffer
**************************

Open it with ‘bmkp-list’ (‘C-x x e’).  This buffer is the heart of the
interactive workflow: filtering, marking, sorting, tagging,
highlighting, editing--everything happens here.

   Major mode: ‘bmkp-list-mode’, derived from ‘special-mode’.

7.1 Header and Mark Columns
===========================

The header shows the current bookmark file and a “title” describing the
current filter (e.g. ‘File and Directory Bookmarks’ or ‘All Bookmarks’).
The mode line shows counts: marked (‘>’), flagged for deletion (‘D’),
tagged (‘t’), temporary (‘X’), annotated (‘a’), modified-unsaved (‘*’),
plus the sort order.  When a counter is split, ‘N/M’ means "N up to and
including the current line, of M total."

   Per-line flags:

Mark        Meaning
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
‘>’         Marked.
‘D’         Flagged for deletion.
‘a’         Has an annotation.
‘t’         Has at least one tag.
‘X’         Temporary--will not be saved.
‘*’         Modified since the last save of the bookmark file.

7.2 Filename Display Style
==========================

Long file paths often get truncated at the right edge of the window,
hiding the basename--which is usually the most informative part of the
path.  The option ‘bmkp-bmenu-filename-style’ controls how the recorded
path is reformatted before display.  It does not change the bookmark
data; only the on-screen rendering.

Value         Example
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
‘full’        ‘/Users/dmg/.emacs.d/modules/bookmark-plusplus/bookmark+-1.el’
‘abbreviate’  ‘~/.emacs.d/modules/bookmark-plusplus/bookmark+-1.el’
‘shrink’      ‘~/.e/m/b/bookmark+-1.el’
‘basename’    ‘bookmark+-1.el’

   The default is ‘abbreviate’.  The ‘shrink’ style collapses each
parent directory to its first character (two characters when the
directory name starts with a dot, so ‘.emacs.d’ becomes ‘.e’ and not
just ‘.’) and always preserves the basename intact.

   Only paths that look like absolute filenames are reformatted.  Buffer
names, ‘location’ strings, and other non-path locations pass through
unchanged.

‘M-F’
     ‘bmkp-bmenu-cycle-filename-style’--cycle the option through ‘full’
     ⇒ ‘abbreviate’ ⇒ ‘shrink’ ⇒ ‘basename’ and re-render the buffer in
     place.

   You can also set the option directly with
‘bmkp-bmenu-set-filename-style’ (which prompts with completion), or
through the Customize interface.  The Casual menu (*note Casual
Integration::) exposes the same cycle entry as ‘M-F’, with a label that
displays the current value.

7.3 Tags Column
===============

By default, the bookmark list shows a single ‘t’ flag for tagged
bookmarks but no indication of _which_ tags they have.  Enable
‘bmkp-bmenu-show-tags-flag’ to add a dedicated tags column between the
bookmark name and the file/location column.  The ‘t’ flag is preserved.

Option                    Effect
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
‘bmkp-bmenu-show-tags-flag’Master switch.  When non-nil, the tags column
                          is rendered.  Default ‘t’.  Set to ‘nil’ to
                          restore the historical layout (name column
                          followed immediately by the file/location
                          column).
‘bmkp-bmenu-tags-column-width’Width of the tags column in characters.
                          Default ‘18’.  Joined tag names exceeding
                          this width are truncated with ‘...’; if
                          shorter, padded with spaces.
‘bmkp-bmenu-name-column-width’Maximum width of the bookmark-name column.
                          ‘nil’ (default) uses the longest current
                          name.  An integer truncates longer names with
                          ‘...’, useful for keeping layout stable when
                          names vary in length.

   Tags are joined with a comma and no space, to maximise information
density.  A bookmark tagged ‘alpha’, ‘beta’, ‘gamma’ in an 18-char
column renders as ‘alpha,beta,gamma ’; in a 12-char column it renders as
‘alpha,beta,...’.

‘M-T’
     ‘bmkp-bmenu-toggle-tags-column’--flip the master switch and
     redisplay.  Reports the new state in the echo area.

   To change widths interactively, use
‘bmkp-bmenu-set-tags-column-width’ and
‘bmkp-bmenu-set-name-column-width’ (both prompt for an integer; pass ‘0’
to the name-width command for ‘auto’).  The Casual menu's Tags submenu
exposes the toggle and both width commands.

   When the tags column is on (or ‘bmkp-bmenu-name-column-width’ is
set), ‘bookmark-bmenu-file-column’ is automatically raised in the buffer
so file paths do not overlap the new columns.  Your custom value, if
larger, is preserved.

7.4 Primary Navigation
======================

Key         Command                       What it does
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
‘n’         ‘next-line’                   Next line.
‘p’         ‘previous-line’               Previous line.
<RET> or    ‘bmkp-list-this-window’       Open in current window.
‘f’
‘o’         ‘bmkp-list-other-window’      Open in other window.
‘C-o’ or    ‘bmkp-list-switch-other-window’Preview in other window;
<TAB>                                     cursor stays here.
‘1’         ‘bmkp-list-1-window’          Display in only one window.
‘2’         ‘bmkp-list-2-window’          Display in two windows.
‘g’         ‘bmkp-bmenu-refresh-menu-list’Refresh (with ‘C-u’: reload
                                          from file).
‘q’         ‘bmkp-bmenu-quit’             Quit.

7.5 Marking and Flagging
========================

The marking scheme follows Dired conventions:

Key         Command                       What it does
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
‘m’         ‘bmkp-list-mark’              Mark this bookmark with ‘>’.
‘u’         ‘bmkp-list-unmark’            Unmark this bookmark.
‘M-m’       ‘bmkp-bmenu-mark-all’         Mark all bookmarks.
‘U’         ‘bmkp-bmenu-unmark-all’       Unmark all (or only ‘>’, or
                                          only ‘D’).
‘M-<DEL>’   ‘bmkp-bmenu-unmark-all’       Same as ‘U’.
‘t’         ‘bmkp-bmenu-toggle-marks’     Swap marked / unmarked.
‘% m’       ‘bmkp-bmenu-regexp-mark’      Mark by regexp.
‘d’ or      ‘bmkp-bmenu-flag-for-deletion’Flag for deletion (‘D’).
‘k’
‘C-d’       ‘bmkp-bmenu-flag-for-deletion-backwards’Flag and move up.
‘x’         ‘bmkp-list-execute-deletions’ Delete all bookmarks flagged
                                          ‘D’.
‘D’         ‘bmkp-bmenu-delete-marked’    Delete all bookmarks marked
                                          ‘>’ (with confirmation).

   The pair ‘d’/‘x’ flags then executes; ‘D’ deletes the ‘>’-marked
bookmarks in one step (after confirmation).

7.6 Filtering and Showing
=========================

‘.’
     Show all bookmarks (clear any filter).
‘>’
     Toggle "show only marked."
‘<’
     Toggle "show only unmarked."
‘M-t’
     Toggle the file/buffer location column.

7.6.1 Filter by Type
--------------------

Keys ending in ‘S’ show only bookmarks of one type; the matching ‘M’
keys mark them instead.  Examples:

     F S    file/dir bookmarks       A S    autofile bookmarks
     B S    non-file bookmarks       Y S    bookmark-file bookmarks
     R S    region bookmarks         Z S    bookmark-list bookmarks
     I S    Info bookmarks           K S    desktop bookmarks
     G S    Gnus bookmarks           V S    variable-list bookmarks
     M S    man-page bookmarks  N S    non-invokable bookmarks
     W E S  EWW bookmarks            w S    snippet bookmarks
     X S    temporary bookmarks      O S    orphaned local-file bookmarks
     # S    autonamed bookmarks      M-d M-s  Dired bookmarks
     T S    tagged bookmarks         T U    untagged bookmarks
     H S    highlighted bookmarks    - S    omitted bookmarks

7.6.2 Incremental Pattern Matching
----------------------------------

Type ‘P PREFIX REGEXP’ and the display narrows as you type.  Press a
non-self-inserting key (e.g. <RET>) to commit.

‘P B’
     Filter by bookmark name.
‘P F’
     Filter by file name.
‘P A’
     Filter by annotation.
‘P T’
     Filter by tag.

7.7 Omitting (vs. Filtering)
============================

Omitting is a stronger form of hiding: omitted bookmarks are hidden from
every view except the dedicated omit view.

‘- >’
     ‘bmkp-bmenu-omit/unomit-marked’--move marked to/from the omit list.
‘- S’
     ‘bmkp-bmenu-show-only-omitted-bookmarks’.
‘- U’
     ‘bmkp-unomit-all’--can also be invoked outside ‘*Bmkp List*’.

7.8 Sorting
===========

Repeat ‘s s’ (‘bmkp-bmenu-change-sort-order-repeat’) to cycle through
every available sort order.  Or pick one directly:

Command                        Key         Sort by
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
‘bmkp-bmenu-sort-by-bookmark-name’‘s n’    Bookmark name.
‘bmkp-bmenu-sort-by-last-bookmark-access’‘s d’Last bookmark access.
‘bmkp-bmenu-sort-by-last-buffer-or-file-access’‘s b’Last buffer/file access.
‘bmkp-bmenu-sort-by-bookmark-type’‘s k’    Bookmark type (kind).
‘bmkp-bmenu-sort-by-file-name’ ‘s f n’     File name.
‘bmkp-bmenu-sort-by-creation-time’‘s 0’    Creation time.
‘bmkp-bmenu-sort-annotated-before-unannotated’‘s a’Annotated first.
‘bmkp-bmenu-sort-flagged-before-unflagged’‘s D’Flagged ‘D’ first.
‘bmkp-bmenu-sort-marked-before-unmarked’‘s >’Marked ‘>’ first.
‘bmkp-reverse-sort-order’      ‘s r’       Reverse direction.

   Sorting is governed by option ‘bmkp-sort-comparer’; the built-in
‘bookmark-sort-flag’ is ignored.

7.9 Editing
===========

Command                        Key         Edits
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
‘bmkp-bmenu-edit-bookmark-name-and-location’‘r’Name and target file
                                           (minibuffer).
‘bmkp-bmenu-edit-bookmark-record’‘e’       Full record (Lisp sexp).
‘bmkp-bmenu-edit-marked’       ‘E’         Records of all marked.
‘bmkp-bmenu-clone-bookmark’    ‘M-n’       Duplicate; default name ends
                                           in ‘<2>’.
‘bmkp-bmenu-edit-tags’         ‘T e’       This bookmark's tags.

7.10 Acting on Marked Bookmarks
===============================

   • ‘bmkp-bmenu-delete-marked’ (‘D’) deletes them.
   • ‘bmkp-bmenu-dired-marked’ (‘M-d >’) opens Dired on the local files
     among them.
   • ‘bmkp-bmenu-query-replace-marked-bookmarks-regexp’ (‘M-q’)
     query-replaces across their targets, in the current sort order.
   • ‘bmkp-bmenu-search-marked-bookmarks-regexp’ (‘M-s a M-s’)
     regexp-searches across their targets.
   • Isearch commands (‘M-s a C-s’ / ‘M-s a M-C-s’) search marked
     targets incrementally.
   • Tag commands (‘T > +/-’) add or remove tags on the marked
     bookmarks.
   • ‘bmkp-bmenu-list-tags-of-marked’ (‘T > l’) lists the union of tags
     of marked bookmarks.
   • ‘bmkp-bmenu-edit-annotations-for-marked’ (‘a >’) edits annotations
     of marked bookmarks.
   • ‘bmkp-bmenu-toggle-marked-temporary/savable’ (‘M-X’) toggles
     temporary / savable on marked bookmarks.
   • Bookmark-file commands (‘Y > +/-/0’) copy, move, or create a new
     bookmark file from marked bookmarks (*note Multiple Bookmark
     Files::).

7.11 Describe / Inspect
=======================

Command                        Key              Shows
