8 Bookmark Types
****************

A bookmark “type” is really just a “handler”: a function that "jumps to"
(acts on) the bookmark.  Bookmark+ ships handlers for around 70 of them.

   Run ‘M-x bmkp-types-alist’ to list every type registered in your
session.  ‘bmkp-jump-to-type’ (‘C-x j :’) lets you pick a type
interactively.  Predicates of the form ‘bmkp-TYPE-bookmark-p’ recognize
each type.

8.1 Location / File Bookmarks
=============================

   • *File / local file / remote file.*  Jumping visits the file.
   • *Directory.*  Like a file bookmark, but the destination is a
     directory.
   • *Non-file (buffer).*  Like a file bookmark for a buffer that is not
     visiting a file.
   • *Region.*  A bookmark with ‘front-context-string’,
     ‘rear-context-string’, plus an ‘end-position’ property.  Jumping
     activates the region (controlled by ‘bmkp-use-region’).
     ‘bmkp-region-jump-narrow-indirect-other-window’ (‘C-x 4 j R’)
     narrows the region into a cloned indirect buffer.

8.2 Autofile Bookmarks
======================

An “autofile” is a bookmark whose name is the non-directory part of its
file name.  ‘bmkp-autofile-set’ (‘C-x x c a’) creates one.  Combined
with tags this gives you a filesystem-wide metadata layer.  Related
options: ‘bmkp-autofile-filecache’ (advise ‘file-cache-add-file’ to also
create autofiles), ‘bmkp-autofile-access-invokes-bookmark-flag’ (make
‘find-file’ also "visit" the autofile, updating its visit count).

8.3 Dired and Dired-Tree Bookmarks
==================================

A Dired bookmark records:

   • the Dired directory,
   • the ‘ls’ switches,
   • which files are marked,
   • which subdirectories are inserted,
   • which subdirectories are hidden.

   Jumping reproduces the Dired buffer with the same markings, inserted
subdirs, and hidden subdirs.  A “Dired-tree bookmark” is a sequence
bookmark whose components are Dired bookmarks for a directory and its
descendants.  ‘diredp-do-bookmark-dirs-recursive’ (from ‘dired+.el’)
creates one for the current Dired buffer.

8.4 Info, ‘man’, EWW, Gnus
==========================

   • *Info.*  ‘bmkp-info-jump’ (‘C-x j i’, or ‘j’ in Info mode).  Mode
     ‘bmkp-info-auto-bookmark-mode’ automatically creates or updates an
     Info bookmark every time you visit a node.
   • *‘man’ / ‘woman’.*  ‘bmkp-man-jump’ (‘C-x j m’).
   • *EWW.* ‘bmkp-eww-jump’ (‘C-x j e’).  EWW can be configured so that
     visiting a page records a bookmark, via
     ‘bmkp-eww-replace-keys-flag’ which rebinds the built-in EWW
     bookmark keys to Bookmark+'s.
   • *Gnus.*  ‘bmkp-gnus-jump’ bookmarks a Gnus article (group, article,
     message-id).
   • *Legacy W3M.* ‘bmkp-w3m-jump’ still recognises legacy W3M bookmarks
     saved by earlier versions of Bookmark+, but opens them in EWW. This
     fork does not create new W3M bookmarks.

8.5 Image Bookmarks
===================

When you bookmark an image-file target, Emacs's image handler is used
automatically.  ‘bmkp-image-jump’ (‘C-x j M-i’) jumps to one; the
description (‘C-h <RET>’) shows the full EXIF metadata (requires
‘exiftool’).

8.6 URL Bookmarks
=================

‘bmkp-url-target-set’ (‘C-x x c u’) and ‘bmkp-url-jump’ (‘C-x j u’).
The handler is typically ‘browse-url’.

8.7 Desktop Bookmarks
=====================

‘bmkp-set-desktop-bookmark’ (‘C-x x K’) captures a desktop (from
‘desktop.el’).  Jumping restores the saved desktop.

   Options:
   • ‘bmkp-desktop-no-save-vars’--variables to exclude.
   • ‘bmkp-desktop-jump-save-before-flag’--save current desktop before
     jumping if it was reached by jumping.
   • ‘bmkp-desktop-save-as-last’--add to ‘kill-emacs-hook’ to remember
     the last jumped-to desktop.

8.8 Sequence (Composite) Bookmarks
==================================

A “sequence bookmark” invokes each member bookmark in turn.
‘bmkp-set-sequence-bookmark’ (‘C-x x c s’) prompts for a sequence name
and the member bookmark names.  ‘bmkp-bmenu-make-sequence-from-marked’
turns the marked bookmarks into a sequence in their current order.
Members may themselves be sequence bookmarks.

8.9 Function and Keyboard-Macro Bookmarks
=========================================

‘bmkp-make-function-bookmark’ (‘C-x x c F’) records a function symbol or
a lambda expression.  With a prefix argument it captures
‘last-kbd-macro’--a persistent way to replay a keyboard macro.
‘bmkp-wrap-bookmark-with-last-kbd-macro’ (‘C-x x c C-k’) builds a
sequence bookmark that first invokes another bookmark and then plays the
macro.

8.10 Variable-List Bookmarks
============================

‘bmkp-set-variable-list-bookmark’ records a set of variables and their
current values.  ‘bmkp-jump-variable-list’ (‘C-x j v’) restores them in
the bookmark's buffer.

8.11 Snippet Bookmarks
======================

‘bmkp-set-snippet-bookmark’ (‘C-x x M-w’) saves the active region's text
under a bookmark name.  At any time, in any Emacs session,
‘bmkp-snippet-to-kill-ring’ (‘C-x j M-w’) yanks the saved snippet to the
kill ring.

8.12 Bookmark-List Bookmarks
============================

A “bookmark-list bookmark” records the state of ‘*Bmkp List*’ (sort
order, filter, regexp pattern, title, omit list).  Jumping to it
restores that state.  Defined as either a real bookmark or as a command
via ‘C-c C-c’ (‘bmkp-bmenu-define-command’).

8.13 Bookmark-File Bookmarks
============================

Created by ‘bmkp-set-bookmark-file-bookmark’ (‘C-x x c y’).  "Jumping"
to one _loads_ the referenced bookmark file.  With ‘C-u’, jumping
_switches_ to it.

8.14 Defining Your Own Types
============================

Define a handler function and set ‘bookmark-make-record-function’ (or
pass a handler via your own bookmark setter).  To register a new type so
‘bmkp-jump-to-type’ recognizes it, provide a function
‘bmkp-TYPE-alist-only’ and call ‘(bmkp-define-history-variables)’.  The
macro ‘bmkp-define-type-from-handler’ (in ‘bookmark+-mac.el’) does all
of this and also generates a predicate ‘bmkp-TYPE-bookmark-p’ and a
"show only" command ‘bmkp-bmenu-show-only-TYPE-bookmarks’.


