9 Tags
******

A bookmark “tag” is a string (or a string plus a Lisp value) attached to
a bookmark.  Tags are persistent.  Multiple bookmarks can share the same
tag; one bookmark can have many.  Tags define _sets_ of bookmarks
(‘blue’, ‘vacation/2024/photos’, ‘todo’, ...) and most Bookmark+
commands can operate on those sets.

9.1 Adding and Removing Tags
============================

Command                        Global key       Bmenu      Action
                                                key
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
‘bmkp-add-tags’ /              ‘C-x x t + b’    ‘T +’      Add tags.
‘bmkp-bmenu-add-tags’
‘bmkp-remove-tags’ /           ‘C-x x t - b’    ‘T -’      Remove tags.
‘bmkp-bmenu-remove-tags’
‘bmkp-remove-all-tags’ /       ‘C-x x t 0’      ‘T 0’      Remove all
‘bmkp-bmenu-remove-all-tags’                               tags.
‘bmkp-autofile-add-tags’       ‘C-x x t + a’    (none)     Tag a file
                                                           (creates
                                                           autofile).
‘bmkp-untag-a-file’            ‘C-x x t - a’    (none)     Untag a file.
‘bmkp-copy-tags’               ‘C-x x t c’      ‘T c’      Copy tags to a
                                                           kill-ring-style
                                                           slot.
‘bmkp-paste-add-tags’          ‘C-x x t p’      ‘T p’      Paste
                                                           (additive).
‘bmkp-paste-replace-tags’      ‘C-x x t q’      ‘T q’      Paste
                                                           (replace).
‘bmkp-rename-tag’              ‘C-x x t r’      ‘T r’      Rename a tag
                                                           everywhere.
‘bmkp-edit-tags’               ‘C-x x t e’      ‘T e’      Edit a
                                                           bookmark's
                                                           tags.
‘bmkp-list-all-tags’           ‘C-x x t l’      ‘T l’      List every
                                                           defined tag.
‘bmkp-set-tag-value’           ‘C-x x t v’      ‘T v’      Give a tag a
                                                           value.

   The tag prompt uses ‘completing-read-multiple’: enter tags in a
single, comma-separated reply (‘work,urgent,backend’).  Each segment
between commas has its own completion against the candidate list.  Press
<RET> on an empty input to accept the empty set (many commands treat
that as "any tag at all").  Use ‘C-q C-j’ to include a newline in a tag.

   Inside ‘*Bmkp List*’, ‘T +’, ‘T -’, ‘T 0’, ‘T v’ and the Casual tags
menu act on the bookmark on the current line - no separate bookmark
prompt.  Outside the list, the ‘bmkp-*’ variants prompt for the bookmark
first.

9.2 Marking by Tag in ‘*Bmkp List*’
===================================

The tag-based mark and unmark commands live under ‘T m’ / ‘T u’:

Command                            Key         Marks/unmarks bookmarks
                                               tagged...
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
‘bmkp-bmenu-mark-bookmarks-tagged-all’‘T m *’  with all of the given
                                               tags.
‘bmkp-bmenu-mark-bookmarks-tagged-some’‘T m +’ with some of them.
‘bmkp-bmenu-mark-bookmarks-tagged-not-all’‘T m ~ *’not with all of them.
‘bmkp-bmenu-mark-bookmarks-tagged-none’‘T m ~ +’with none of them.
‘bmkp-bmenu-mark-bookmarks-tagged-regexp’‘T m %’with a tag matching a
                                               regexp.
‘bmkp-bmenu-show-only-tagged-bookmarks’‘T S’   show only tagged.
‘bmkp-bmenu-show-only-untagged-bookmarks’‘T U’ show only untagged.

   A prefix argument flips "some" / "not all" and "all" / "none."

9.3 Tag Values
==============

Use ‘bmkp-set-tag-value’ (‘T v’ in ‘*Bmkp List*’) to give a tag any
readable Lisp value: number, string, list, etc.  A tag with a value is
internally ‘(NAME . VALUE)’.  Most Bookmark+ commands ignore values; you
can use them from your own Lisp.

   A single predefined tag has special behaviour: ‘bmkp-jump’.  If its
value is a function, that function is called just after
‘bookmark-after-jump-hook’ runs for the tagged bookmark.

   Tag names prefixed with ‘bmkp-’ are reserved.

9.4 Pseudo-Hierarchical Tags
============================

A simple convention--tag names that look like paths
(‘vacation/2024/winter/photos’)--gives you a tree-shaped organization
without any special syntax.  Use completion (<TAB>) on partial prefixes
to descend the "tree."


