10 Annotations
**************

An annotation is free-text metadata attached to a bookmark.

‘bmkp-annotate-bookmark’
     ‘C-x x a a’.  Prompts for a bookmark and opens an annotation edit
     buffer.
‘bookmark-show-annotation’
     ‘C-x x a s’.  Shows an annotation in read-only mode (‘C-x C-q’
     toggles to edit mode).
‘bookmark-show-all-annotations’
     ‘C-x x a S’.
‘bmkp-annotate-bookmark-this-file/buffer’
     ‘C-x x a b’.
‘bmkp-annotate-all-bookmarks-this-file/buffer’
     ‘C-x x a B’.

   In the edit buffer:

   • ‘bookmark-send-edited-annotation’ saves (‘C-c C-c’; or ‘C-c C-M-c’
     when Org mode owns ‘C-c C-c’).
   • ‘bookmark-kill-annotation’ (‘C-x C-k’) discards changes.
   • The buffer's major mode is controlled by
     ‘bmkp-annotation-modes-inherit-from’ (default ‘org-mode’).
   • ‘bookmark-automatically-show-annotations’--if non-nil, jumping to a
     bookmark pops up its annotation.

10.1 External Annotations ("Annotation Forwards")
=================================================

Keep the inline annotation short and "forward" to a file, URL, or
another bookmark.  Put one of these as the first non-blank line:

     bmkp-annot-url: "FILE"      ; opens with find-file-other-window
     bmkp-annot-url: "URL"       ; opens with browse-url
     bmkp-annot-url: "BOOKMARK"  ; jumps to the named bookmark

   When you _show_ the annotation, Bookmark+ follows the forward.  When
you _edit_ it (‘a e’), you still see the literal text.

10.2 Annotation Commands in ‘*Bmkp List*’
=========================================

