11 Multiple Bookmark Files
**************************

A bookmark file is a physical file on disk containing complete bookmark
records.  Bookmark+ makes it easy to:

   • Switch to a different bookmark file (replacing the current
     in-memory set).
   • Accumulate bookmarks by loading additional files.
   • Save the current bookmarks to a different file with
     ‘bookmark-write’ (‘C-x x w’).
   • Create an empty bookmark file with ‘bmkp-empty-file’ (‘C-x x 0’).

11.1 Switching
==============

Command                            Key           Meaning
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
‘bmkp-switch-bookmark-file-create’ ‘C-x x L’     Switch to another
                                   or ‘L’        bookmark file.
‘bmkp-load’ (no prefix)            ‘C-x x l’     Add bookmarks from a
                                   or ‘l’        file.
‘bmkp-load’ (with prefix)          ‘C-u C-x x    Equivalent to ‘L’
                                   l’            (switch).
‘bmkp-switch-to-bookmark-file-this-file/buffer’‘C-x x C-l’Switch to a file with
                                                 only this buffer's
                                                 bookmarks.
‘bmkp-bmenu-load-marked-bookmark-file-bookmarks’‘M-l’Load every marked
                                                 bookmark-file bookmark.

11.2 Copying / Moving / Creating
================================

Command                            Key         Meaning
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
‘bmkp-bmenu-copy-marked-to-bookmark-file’‘Y > +’Copy marked to another
                                               bookmark file.
‘bmkp-bmenu-move-marked-to-bookmark-file’‘Y > -’Move them.
‘bmkp-bmenu-create-bookmark-file-from-marked’‘Y > 0’New file from marked.

11.3 Bookmark-File Bookmarks
============================

Created with ‘bmkp-set-bookmark-file-bookmark’ (‘C-x x c y’).  "Jumping"
to one _loads_ that bookmark file; with ‘C-u’ it _switches_ to it.

11.4 Default for the Next Session
=================================

The default bookmark file for the next Emacs session is the one in use
when you quit, controlled by ‘bmkp-last-as-first-bookmark-file’.  Set
this to ‘nil’ to always start from ‘bookmark-default-file’.

   Bookmark files are _physical_, not logical, groupings.  Copying a
bookmark from one to another duplicates it; the two copies are
independent thereafter.


