17 Autonamed Bookmarks
**********************

An “autonamed” bookmark is a regular, persistent bookmark whose name is
generated automatically from a buffer name plus position (default
format: ‘000058356 foo.el’--nine-digit position then buffer name).  It
records no region, only a position.

‘bmkp-toggle-autonamed-bookmark-set/delete’
     ‘C-x x <RET>’.  Toggles the autonamed bookmark at point.  Setting
     one is one keystroke; deleting it is the same keystroke.  With a
     prefix argument it deletes _all_ autonamed bookmarks in the current
     buffer (after confirmation).
‘bmkp-delete-bookmarks’
     ‘C-x x <delete>’.  Deletes individual bookmarks under cursor or all
     bookmarks in the buffer (any type).

   Other autonamed commands (not bound by default):
‘bmkp-set-autonamed-bookmark-at-line’,
‘bmkp-set-autonamed-regexp-buffer’, ‘bmkp-set-autonamed-regexp-region’,
‘bmkp-occur-create-autonamed-bookmarks’.

   If you do not want autonamed bookmarks to persist across sessions:

     (add-hook 'kill-buffer-hook 'bmkp-delete-autonamed-this-buffer-no-confirm)
     (add-hook 'kill-emacs-hook  'bmkp-delete-autonamed-no-confirm)

   Alternative: make autonamed bookmarks _temporary_ via
‘bmkp-autotemp-bookmark-predicates’ (the default), and they will not be
saved.  *Note Temporary Bookmarks::.

   Customize the name format with ‘bmkp-autoname-format’ and
‘bmkp-autoname-bookmark-function’.  The special spec ‘%B’ refers to the
buffer name within the format.


