19 Bookmark Records
*******************

A bookmark is a list whose ‘car’ is its name (a string) and whose ‘cdr’
is a “property alist”.  A typical record:

     ("README"
      (id          . "8f3a7b3c-4dd5-...")
      (filename    . "/home/me/proj/README")
      (front-context-string . "## Introduction")
      (rear-context-string  . "")
      (position    . 1234)
      (last-modified 26013 12345 0 0)
      (visits      . 7)
      (tags ("doc") ("project" . "myproj")))

   Every record carries an ‘(id . STRING)’ property.  The id is opaque
(‘format-time-string’ plus random hex bits), assigned at record creation
by ‘bookmark-make-record-default’.  Records read from a file that lack
an ‘id’ (created by the built-in or by older Bookmark+ versions) get one
generated at load time and the alist is marked dirty so the next save
writes them.

   *Note Migration::, for why the ‘id’ field exists and how it relates
to bookmark identity.

19.1 Lookup Helpers
===================

‘bmkp-get-bookmark’
     ‘(assoc NAME bookmark-alist)’.  Names are unique.
‘bmkp-get-by-id’
     Find a record by id.  Useful when a bookmark name may have changed.

19.2 Name Uniqueness
====================

Bookmark names are enforced unique within ‘bookmark-alist’.  Two
mechanisms maintain this:

   • *Auto-disambiguation on creation.*  When ‘bookmark-store’ is asked
     to create a new bookmark whose name collides with an existing one,
     the new bookmark is auto-renamed ‘foo’ ⇒ ‘foo<2>’ ⇒ ‘foo<3>’ ⇒ ...
   • *Deduplication on load.*  ‘bmkp-deduplicate-bookmark-names’ runs on
     ‘bmkp-read-bookmark-file-hook’ and renames any duplicate names
     found in a loaded bookmark file.

19.3 Reading and Writing Bookmark Files
=======================================

Bookmark files written by this fork are plain printable Lisp.  No
‘print-circle’ markers, no shared structure: just the bookmark alist as
a single readable form.

   The format is identical to what built-in ‘bookmark.el’ writes, with
one extra alist entry per record:

     (id . "20260601T144831-3f5a7c")

   The built-in ignores this entry on read and preserves it on write.

19.3.1 Caveat: the Built-in Strips Metadata on Re-Set
-----------------------------------------------------

The interop is safe _as long as the built-in does not modify the
record_.  When the built-in only loads a file, displays it, and saves it
back, every alist entry that built-in ‘bookmark.el’ does not recognise
is preserved verbatim -- including the ‘id’, tags, annotation, visit
count, last-access time, lighting override, and any other Bookmark++
property.

   However, the built-in's ‘bookmark-set’ (and the commands that call
it, including ‘C-x r m’) does not _update_ an existing record: it
_rebuilds_ it from scratch using ‘bookmark-make-record-default’.
Built-in ‘bookmark-make-record-default’ only knows about the standard
‘bookmark.el’ properties.  The result: if you have a bookmark named
‘notes’ carrying Bookmark++ metadata (tags, ‘annotation’, ‘id’, etc.)
and you re-set it from a vanilla Emacs session via ‘C-x r m notes RET’,
the new record overwrites the old, and all of those properties are gone.
When the file is saved next, the metadata is lost on disk too.

   To avoid this:

   • If you have to edit a Bookmark++ file from a vanilla Emacs session,
     treat it as read-only -- jump to bookmarks, but do not ‘C-x r m’ to
     update one in place.
   • If you regularly use both vanilla Emacs and Bookmark++ on the same
     machine, keep them on _different_ bookmark files.  *Note Multiple
     Bookmark Files::, for how to switch.
   • If you accidentally re-set a bookmark from a vanilla session, you
     can recover from a backup written by Bookmark++ (set
     ‘bookmark-version-control’ to ‘t’; backups are kept next to the
     bookmark file as ‘~/.emacs.bmk.~1~’ etc.).

   *Note Migration::, for the rationale behind the ‘id’ field and the
file-format simplification.


