21 Migration from Upstream Bookmark+
************************************

This is a fork of Drew Adams' Bookmark+, modernized for Emacs 30+.  If
you are coming from the original, here is what changed.

21.1 Sibling, Not Replacement
=============================

Upstream Bookmark+ _replaced_ many built-in ‘bookmark.el’ functions in
place: ‘bookmark-set’, ‘bookmark-store’, ‘bookmark-get-bookmark’, the
bmenu rendering, and more.  The replacements were richer, but they also
tightly coupled Bookmark+ to every change in the built-in.

   This fork is an *additive sibling*.  No built-in function is
redefined.  Every command lives under the ‘bmkp-’ prefix.  Both systems
coexist and operate on the same ‘bookmark-alist’ and the same on-disk
bookmark file; you can call either at any time.

   The architectural change that made this possible is the new ‘id’
field, described next.

21.2 The ‘id’ Field: Identity in This Fork
==========================================

The single most important difference between this fork and upstream
Bookmark+ is how bookmarks are identified internally.  Understanding
this matters if you write Emacs Lisp that manipulates bookmarks; it
matters less for interactive use.

21.2.1 What Upstream Did
------------------------

The user-visible effect upstream achieved was simple: *two bookmarks
could have the exact same display name*.  This was useful for the
“autofile” pattern -- creating bookmarks named after files (e.g. many
‘README.md’ files, one per project), all sharing the same short name.

   Internally, upstream got this by attaching a hidden tag to each
bookmark's name string.  Even though two name strings displayed as the
same text, they carried different hidden tags pointing to different
records, so the code could still tell them apart.  Emacs calls these
hidden tags “text properties” on strings; the specific tag was called
‘bmkp-full-record’.

   The same hidden-tag trick also bought upstream three pieces of
internal speed and convenience that did not affect what the user saw,
but mattered to the implementation:

  1. Going from a name to its record was a single hidden-tag read
     instead of a search through the bookmark list.
  2. Programs holding an old name string still worked after the bookmark
     was renamed in the list -- the hidden tag still pointed at the same
     record.
  3. Each row in ‘*Bmkp List*’ carried its own record in the hidden tag
     of the displayed name, so the bmenu code didn't need to look up the
     name to find the record.

   The cost was paid in the on-disk file format.  Hidden tags on shared
strings can only be saved if Emacs is told to preserve shared-structure
(‘print-circle’); the resulting bookmark file contained markers like
‘#1=#1#’.  Files written this way could not be safely read and
re-written by Emacs's built-in ‘bookmark.el’, which does not turn on
shared-structure preservation when it writes.

21.2.2 What This Fork Does
--------------------------

Every bookmark record carries an opaque ‘(id . STRING)’ property:

     ("README.md"
      (id . "20260601T144831-3f5a7c")
      (filename . "/home/me/proj/README.md")
      (position . 1234)
      ...)

   The id is generated by ‘bookmark-make-record-default’ at record
creation time.  It uses ‘format-time-string’ plus a few random hex bits,
giving an opaque, sortable, collision-resistant key.  Records read from
a file that lack an id (written by built-in ‘bookmark.el’ or older
Bookmark+) have one generated at load time, and the alist is marked
dirty so the next save persists them.

   Names are now enforced unique within ‘bookmark-alist’ by
auto-disambiguation: if ‘bmkp-store’ is asked to create a new bookmark
whose name collides with an existing one, the new bookmark is renamed
‘foo’ ⇒ ‘foo<2>’ ⇒ ‘foo<3>’ ⇒ ... before being added.  Files written by
older versions with duplicate names are deduplicated on load by
‘bmkp-deduplicate-bookmark-names’.

21.2.3 What Changed in Practice
-------------------------------

Compared with upstream:

Capability                       This fork
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
Display-identical duplicate      Auto-disambiguated as ‘foo’, ‘foo<2>’,
names                            ...
Looking up a record from its     Search through the list (was a
name                             constant-time tag read)
Programs holding a name across   Should hold the ‘id’ instead (see
a rename                         Practical Guidance)
Each ‘*Bmkp List*’ row as its    Read the line, then look up the name
own record handle

   The first row is the only user-visible change.  An autofile use case
(many ‘README.md’ in different directories) that previously showed two
identical-looking rows now shows ‘README.md’ and ‘README.md<2>’.  The
behavior is the same; the visual is different.

   The other three rows are invisible to interactive users.
Programmatic callers may need adjustment -- see Practical Guidance
below.

21.2.4 What This Fork Gained
----------------------------

   • *Plain printable file format.*  No ‘print-circle’ markers, no
     shared-structure tricks.  Bookmark files are valid input to ‘read’
     under any settings.  About 300-400 lines of property machinery,
     file-write gymnastics, and "maybe-unpropertize" helpers were
     deleted from the source.
   • *Interop with the built-in.*  A file written by this fork is read
     by built-in ‘bookmark.el’; a file written by the built-in is read
     by this fork (and the ‘bmkp-read-bookmark-file-hook’ backfills any
     missing ‘id’ fields at load time).  Records the built-in does not
     modify are written back unchanged.  See *note Round Trip Caveat::,
     for the one important caveat when the built-in _modifies_ a record.
   • *The sibling architecture itself.*  Without giving up the
     hidden-tag trick, this fork could not stop redefining
     ‘bookmark-store’, ‘bookmark-get-bookmark’, and friends.  The id
     field made the sibling design possible.
   • *Identity that survives rename.*  The id lives in the record, so
     renaming a bookmark in place preserves the id.  Sequence bookmarks
     and bookmark-list bookmarks can safely reference their components
     by id rather than by name.

21.2.5 Practical Guidance for Lisp Callers
------------------------------------------

If you write Emacs Lisp that holds a reference to a bookmark across
edits, renames, file reloads, or sessions: *hold the id, not the name*.
The name is a display label and may change at any time; the id is
stable.

     ;; Save:
     (let ((id (bookmark-prop-get "my-bookmark" 'id)))
       ;; ... stash id somewhere ...
       )

     ;; Retrieve later, even if "my-bookmark" was renamed:
     (let ((rec (bmkp-get-by-id stored-id)))
       (when rec
         (bmkp-jump (bookmark-name-from-full-record rec))))

   For ad-hoc interactive use the name is fine; the rename window is
small and the consequences of staleness are usually just a ‘No such
bookmark’ error.

21.3 No Compatibility Aliases
=============================

Where this fork renamed an upstream symbol (for example, the bmenu
buffer became ‘*Bmkp List*’ and many ‘bookmark-bmenu-*’ defuns became
‘bmkp-list-*’), no compatibility alias was kept.  The user-visible
Bookmark+ commands are all ‘bmkp-*’; the built-in ‘bookmark-*’ names
always refer to the built-in.

   If you had user code that called ‘bookmark-bmenu-foo’, point it at
the corresponding ‘bmkp-list-foo’ or ‘bmkp-bmenu-foo’.

21.4 Emacs 30 or Newer Required
===============================

Loading the package on Emacs < 30 signals an error at load time.  Many
polyfills for older Emacs (cl-puthash dispatch, find-tag-default
fallbacks, Emacs-21 fringe-style guards, ...) have been deleted.

21.5 Dropped External Dependencies
==================================

Replaced with built-in equivalents:

Upstream dep              Replacement
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
‘crosshairs.el’           Built-in ‘pulse.el’.
‘fit-frame.el’            Built-in ‘fit-frame-to-buffer’.
‘narrow-indirect.el’      Built-in ‘clone-indirect-buffer-other-window’
                          + ‘narrow-to-region’.
‘thingatpt+.el’           Inlined as ‘bmkp-symbol-nearest-point’ and
                          friends.
‘zones.el’ helper calls   Inlined as ‘bmkp-read-any-variable’,
                          ‘bmkp-readable-marker’ (the izones bookmark
                          type is still gated on ‘zones.el’).
‘linkd.el’ (dead since    Built-in ‘outline-minor-mode’.
2007)
Active ‘emacs-w3m’        ‘bmkp-jump-w3m’ routes to ‘bmkp-jump-eww’; no
integration               new W3M bookmarks created.
Icicles                   Plain ‘completing-read’; layer ‘vertico’ /
completion-framework      ‘consult’ / ‘marginalia’ on top.
integration

   ‘dired+.el’ is still recognised as an optional dependency.

21.6 File Format
================

Bookmark files are now plain printable Lisp--no ‘print-circle’/‘#1=#1#’
markers, no ‘bmkp-full-record’ text property on names.  Files round-trip
through built-in ‘bookmark.el’ losslessly.

21.7 New Capabilities
=====================

   • Live preview in ‘*Bmkp List*’ via ‘bmkp-list-preview-mode’ (*Note
     Live Preview::).
   • ‘consult’ integration for ‘bmkp-jump’ (same chapter).
   • Optional Casual-style Transient menu via ‘casual-bmkp.el’ (*Note
     Casual Integration::).
   • Stable bookmark identity via the ‘id’ record property.
   • Hard Emacs-30 gate, much cleaner source (~600 lines of dead
     version-gates and polyfills removed).


